BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
Let [`P(n)`] be the statement [`\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}2^n \lt  n!\text{.}`] We will show [`P(n)`] is true for all [`n \ge 4\text{.}`] First, we check the base case and see that yes, [`\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}2^4 \lt  4!`] (as [`\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}16 \lt  24`]) so [`P(4)`] is true. Now for the inductive case. Assume [`P(k)`] is true for an arbitrary [`k \ge 4\text{.}`] That is, [`\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}2^k \lt  k!\text{.}`] Now consider [`P(k+1)\text{:}`] [`\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}2^{k+1} \lt  (k+1)!\text{.}`] To prove this, we start with the left side and work to the right side.

[```\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}\newcommand{\gt}{>}\newcommand{\amp}{&}\begin{aligned}
2^{k+1}~ \amp = 2\cdot 2^k \amp\\
\amp \lt 2\cdot k! \amp \text{by the inductive hypothesis}\\
\amp \lt (k+1) \cdot k! \amp \text{ since } k+1 \gt 2\\
\amp = (k+1)! \amp
\end{aligned}```]

Therefore [`\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}2^{k+1} \lt (k+1)!`] so we have established [`P(k+1)\text{.}`] Thus by the principle of mathematical induction [`P(n)`] is true for all [`n \ge 4\text{.}`]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

